#### <a id='tagging-cli'></a>Tag Your Clusters Using the PKS CLI 

To apply tags to your cluster's VMs, include the `--tags` parameter in your 
`pks <%= current_page.data.pkscommand %>-cluster` command line, 
and specify the desired tags as a comma-delimited list of `key:value` pairs. 

For example:

<% if current_page.data.pkscommand == "create" %>
<pre class="terminal">
$ pks create-cluster my-cluster --tags "status:billable"
$ pks create-cluster my-cluster --tags "status:non-billable,region:northwest"
$ pks create-cluster my-cluster --tags "client:example.com, costcenter:pettycash"
</pre>
<% else %>
<pre class="terminal">
$ pks update-cluster my-cluster --tags "client:tinymegacorp"
$ pks update-cluster my-cluster --tags "client:example.com,costcenter:pettycash"
$ pks update-cluster my-cluster --tags "status:non-billable, region:northwest"
</pre>
<% end %> 
<p class="note"><strong>Note</strong>: <%= vars.product_short %> supports tagging on Azure only.
</p>

<p class="note"><strong>Note</strong>: <%= vars.product_short %> Cluster tagging requires Ops Manager v2.8.0 or later.
</p>
<% if current_page.data.pkscommand == "update" %>
When you modify tags using <code>pks update-cluster</code> all of the cluster's 
existing tags are completely overwritten:  

* To add or modify a tag, re-specify the complete 
list of all of the cluster's existing tags, modified with the desired changes. 
* To remove a tag, re-specify the complete 
list of all of the cluster's existing tags without the item to be removed.  

<p class="note"><strong>Note:</strong> To determine a cluster's existing 
tags use <code>pks cluster</code>. 
For information on <code>pks cluster</code> see <a href="#tagging-review">Review Your Tags</a>, below.
</p>
<% end %> 

#### <a id='tagging-review'></a>Review Your Tags

To review the tags applied to a cluster, run `pks cluster`. 

For example:
<pre class="terminal">$ pks cluster my-cluster
Name:                     my-cluster
Plan Name:                large
UUID:                     01a234bc-d56e-7f89-01a2-3b4cde5f6789
Last Action:              CREATE
Last Action State:        succeeded
Last Action Description:  Instance provisioning completed
Kubernetes Master Host:   my-cluster.example.com
Kubernetes Master Port:   8443
Worker Instances:         3
Kubernetes Master IP(s):  192.168.20.7
Tags:                     client:tinymegacorp  costcenter:pettycash
</pre>

<p class="note"><strong>Note:</strong> The <code>pks cluster</code> function returns 
only the custom tags you've applied to the cluster using the PKS CLI.
Your IaaS-provided management console will display both the custom tags you've applied
and the <%= vars.product_short %>-generated system tags. 
Do not use the management console to modify your custom tags.
</p>